Module 1 : Network Architecture
# ðŸŒ Network & Network Security â€” GitHub Notes

> **Source:** Google Cybersecurity Certificate â€“ *Connect and Protect: Networks and Network Security*
>
> **Language:** Bangla + English (easy + exam-ready)

---

## 1ï¸âƒ£ What is a Network?

A **network** is a system where multiple devices communicate and exchange data.

* Data is sent as **packets**
* A packet contains:

  * **Source** (who sends)
  * **Destination** (who receives)
  * **Data (body)**

---

## 2ï¸âƒ£ Network Devices (Core Components)

Devices that control, forward, and secure network traffic.

### ðŸ”¹ Common Network Devices

* **Router** â€“ Connects different networks (Layer 3)
* **Switch** â€“ Connects devices inside a LAN (Layer 2)
* **Firewall** â€“ Filters traffic (security gate)
* **Server** â€“ Provides services to clients
* **Modem** â€“ Connects ISP to internal network
* **Wireless Access Point (WAP)** â€“ Provides Wiâ€‘Fi

### ðŸ”¹ End Devices

* Computer, Laptop, Mobile, Tablet
* Each device has:

  * **MAC Address** (hardware ID)
  * **IP Address** (network ID)
  * **NIC** (Network Interface Card)

---

## 3ï¸âƒ£ Firewall

Firewall is the **first line of defense** in a network.

### What it does:

* Inspects incoming & outgoing traffic
* Blocks suspicious or unauthorized traffic

ðŸ“ Usually placed between **internal network & internet**

> Firewall â‰  only defense, but a critical one

---

## 4ï¸âƒ£ Server & Client-Server Model

### Server

A device that provides services to other devices (**clients**).

**Examples:**

* DNS Server â€“ resolves domain names
* File Server â€“ stores files
* Mail Server â€“ handles emails

### Client-Server Flow

Client â†’ Request â†’ Server â†’ Response

---

## 5ï¸âƒ£ Hub vs Switch

### Hub (Legacy)

* Broadcasts data to all devices
* Low security
* Easy eavesdropping

### Switch (Modern)

* Sends data only to intended device
* Uses **MAC address table**
* Faster & more secure

ðŸ“Œ Works at **Data Link Layer (Layer 2)**

---

## 6ï¸âƒ£ Router

### What Router Does

* Routes data between different networks
* Uses **IP addresses** to make decisions

ðŸ“Œ Works at **Network Layer (Layer 3)**

Many routers include **firewall features**

---

## 7ï¸âƒ£ Modem

* Connects ISP to your network
* Converts signals to digital data

Typical flow:
ISP â†’ Modem â†’ Router â†’ Internal Network

---

## 8ï¸âƒ£ Wireless Access Point (WAP)

* Broadcasts Wiâ€‘Fi using radio waves
* Connects wireless devices to wired network

---

## 9ï¸âƒ£ Network Diagram

A **visual map** of the network.

### Shows:

* Device placement
* Connections
* Traffic flow

### Used by Security Analysts to:

* Understand structure
* Identify vulnerabilities
* Plan defenses

---

## â˜ï¸ Cloud Computing

### On-Premise Network

* Hardware hosted in office
* High cost & maintenance
* Hard to scale

### Cloud Computing

Using **remote servers via internet**.

**CSP Examples:**

* AWS
* Google Cloud
* Microsoft Azure

---

## Cloud Service Models

| Model | You Manage        |
| ----- | ----------------- |
| SaaS  | Nothing           |
| PaaS  | Code              |
| IaaS  | OS + Applications |

---

## Hybrid & Multi-Cloud

* **Hybrid Cloud:** Onâ€‘prem + Cloud (most common)
* **Multiâ€‘Cloud:** Multiple CSPs

---

## Software-Defined Networking (SDN)

Traditional â†’ Physical control
Modern â†’ Software control

SDN includes:

* Virtual routers
* Virtual switches
* Virtual firewalls
* Virtual IDS/IPS

### Benefits

* Fast configuration
* Scalable
* Cloudâ€‘friendly

---

## TCP/IP Communication Basics

### Data Packet Structure

* Header (IP, MAC)
* Body (data)
* Footer (end signal)

---

## TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)

**Reliable & connectionâ€‘oriented**

### Key Features

* 3â€‘Way Handshake (SYN â†’ SYNâ€‘ACK â†’ ACK)
* Packet ordering
* Retransmission
* Flow control
* Error detection

ðŸ” Attacks:

* SYN Flood
* Session Hijacking

---

## IP (Internet Protocol)

### What IP Does

* Logical addressing
* Packet routing

### IP Does NOT

* Guarantee delivery
* Maintain order

ðŸ” Threats:

* IP spoofing
* Packet sniffing

---

## Ports

| Range       | Type       |
| ----------- | ---------- |
| 0â€“1023      | Well-known |
| 1024â€“49151  | Registered |
| 49152â€“65535 | Dynamic    |

### Common Ports

* 80 â€“ HTTP
* 443 â€“ HTTPS
* 22 â€“ SSH
* 25 â€“ SMTP
* 53 â€“ DNS

---

## TCP/IP Model Layers

1. **Network Access** â€“ Ethernet, Wiâ€‘Fi, MAC
2. **Internet** â€“ IP, routing
3. **Transport** â€“ TCP, UDP, ports
4. **Application** â€“ HTTP, DNS, SMTP

---

## IP Address vs MAC Address

| Feature | IP       | MAC      |
| ------- | -------- | -------- |
| Purpose | Location | Identity |
| Scope   | Network  | Local    |
| Changes | Yes      | No       |

---

## IPv4 vs IPv6

| Feature   | IPv4    | IPv6    |
| --------- | ------- | ------- |
| Size      | 32â€‘bit  | 128â€‘bit |
| Addresses | ~4.3B   | Huge    |
| Security  | Limited | Better  |

---

## Security Analyst Key Takeaways

* Network diagrams reveal attack surface
* Switch > Hub for security
* Firewall is critical
* TCP ensures reliability
* IP enables routing
* Ports define application traffic

---

## ðŸ§  Oneâ€‘Line Memory Trick

**Devices â†’ Switch â†’ Router â†’ Internet**

**Firewall protects â†’ Server serves â†’ Diagram explains**

---

