# ðŸŒ Network Protocols, Security & VPN â€” Exam-Ready Notes (Short + Clear)

## ðŸ”¹ What is a Network Protocol?

A **network protocol** is a set of rules that define:

* How data is sent
* In what order
* Data format
* What happens after receiving data

ðŸ§  Think: **Traffic rules of the Internet** ðŸš¦

---

## ðŸ§© Protocol Categories (3 Types)

### 1ï¸âƒ£ Communication Protocols

Used to **send & receive data**

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Management Protocols

Used to **monitor, manage & troubleshoot networks**

### 3ï¸âƒ£ Security Protocols

Used to **protect data using encryption & authentication**

---

## ðŸ“± Application Layer Protocols (Directly used by apps)

| Protocol | Full Form                           | Port     | Use                  | Security        |
| -------- | ----------------------------------- | -------- | -------------------- | --------------- |
| HTTP     | HyperText Transfer Protocol         | 80       | Web pages            | âŒ Not secure    |
| HTTPS    | HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure  | 443      | Secure web           | âœ… TLS/SSL       |
| FTP      | File Transfer Protocol              | 21       | File transfer        | âŒ Plaintext     |
| SFTP     | SSH File Transfer Protocol          | 22       | Secure file transfer | âœ… Encrypted     |
| SMTP     | Simple Mail Transfer Protocol       | 25 / 587 | Send email           | âš ï¸ Needs TLS    |
| POP3     | Post Office Protocol v3             | 110      | Download email       | âŒ Old           |
| IMAP     | Internet Message Access Protocol    | 143      | Sync email           | âš ï¸ Needs TLS    |
| DNS      | Domain Name System                  | 53       | Name â†’ IP            | âš ï¸ Spoofable    |
| DHCP     | Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol | â€”        | Assign IP            | âš ï¸ Trust based  |
| SNMP     | Simple Network Management Protocol  | â€”        | Monitoring           | âš ï¸ Misuse risk  |
| NTP      | Network Time Protocol               | 123      | Time sync            | âš ï¸ Time attacks |
| Telnet   | Teletype Network                    | 23       | Remote access        | âŒ Insecure      |
| SSH      | Secure Shell                        | 22       | Secure remote access | âœ… Encrypted     |

---

## ðŸšš Transport Layer Protocols

### âœ… TCP â€” Transmission Control Protocol

* Reliable & ordered delivery
* Connection-oriented (3-way handshake)
* Used by: HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SMTP

### âš¡ UDP â€” User Datagram Protocol

* Fast, no guarantee
* Connectionless
* Used by: DNS, VoIP, Streaming, Games

---

## ðŸŒ Internet Layer Protocols

| Protocol | Full Form                         | Purpose              |
| -------- | --------------------------------- | -------------------- |
| IP       | Internet Protocol                 | Addressing & routing |
| ICMP     | Internet Control Message Protocol | Errors, ping         |
| IPsec    | Internet Protocol Security        | Encrypted IP traffic |

---

## ðŸ–§ Network Access Layer Protocols

| Protocol | Full Form                   | Purpose           |
| -------- | --------------------------- | ----------------- |
| ARP      | Address Resolution Protocol | IP â†’ MAC          |
| Ethernet | â€”                           | Wired LAN         |
| Wi-Fi    | IEEE 802.11                 | Wireless LAN      |
| PPP      | Point-to-Point Protocol     | Direct connection |

---

## ðŸ” Security Protocols (Analyst Focus)

| Protocol | Full Meaning               | Use               |
| -------- | -------------------------- | ----------------- |
| SSL      | Secure Sockets Layer       | Old encryption    |
| TLS      | Transport Layer Security   | Modern encryption |
| HTTPS    | HTTP over TLS              | Secure web        |
| SSH      | Secure Shell               | Secure login      |
| SFTP     | SSH File Transfer Protocol | Secure files      |
| IPsec    | Internet Protocol Security | VPN, tunnels      |

âš ï¸ **Encryption does NOT hide IP addresses**

---

## ðŸ“¡ Wi-Fi Security Protocols (Evolution)

| Protocol | Year | Encryption | Status        |
| -------- | ---- | ---------- | ------------- |
| WEP      | 1999 | Weak       | âŒ Broken      |
| WPA      | 2003 | TKIP       | âŒ Vulnerable  |
| WPA2     | 2004 | AES        | âš ï¸ Acceptable |
| WPA3     | 2018 | SAE + AES  | âœ… Best        |

### WPA Modes

* **Personal** â†’ Shared password (Home)
* **Enterprise** â†’ Individual login (Business)

---

## ðŸ›¡ï¸ VPN â€” Virtual Private Network

### Why VPN?

* Hides public IP
* Encrypts data
* Prevents tracking

### How VPN Works

* Device â†” VPN Server â†” Internet
* Uses **encryption + tunneling + encapsulation**

---

## ðŸ” VPN Types

### 1ï¸âƒ£ Remote Access VPN

* User â†” VPN server
* Personal & enterprise use

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Site-to-Site VPN

* Network â†” Network
* Uses **IPsec**

---

## ðŸ”‘ VPN Protocols

| Protocol  | Use          | Speed  | Notes          |
| --------- | ------------ | ------ | -------------- |
| IPsec     | Site-to-Site | Medium | Older, trusted |
| WireGuard | Both         | Fast   | Modern, simple |

---

## ðŸ§± Security Zones

Internet
â†“
Uncontrolled Zone
â†“
DMZ (Public servers)
â†“
Internal Network
â†“
Restricted Zone (Sensitive data)

---

## ðŸ”¢ Subnetting & CIDR

### Subnetting

* Large network â†’ smaller networks
* Improves **security + performance**

### CIDR â€” Classless Inter-Domain Routing

Format: `IP/Prefix`
Example: `192.168.1.0/24`

Benefits:

* Saves IPv4
* Flexible
* Smaller routing tables

---

## ðŸ§ Proxy Server

| Type          | Purpose          |
| ------------- | ---------------- |
| Forward Proxy | Protects users   |
| Reverse Proxy | Protects servers |
| Email Proxy   | Filters spam     |

---

## ðŸ”¥ Firewalls

| Type      | Feature             |
| --------- | ------------------- |
| Stateless | Rule-based          |
| Stateful  | Tracks sessions     |
| NGFW      | DPI, IPS, App-aware |

---

## âœ… Final One-Look Takeaways

* Protocols = rules of networking
* TCP = reliable, UDP = fast
* HTTPS, SSH, VPN = security backbone
* WPA3 > WPA2 > WPA > WEP
* Subnetting + Security zones = defense strategy
* Proxy, Firewall, VPN = core protection tools

